The paper deals with the problem of autonomous navigation in partially known environments, which is a common topic in robotics (cs.RO). The use of a state-dependent distance metric and virtual reference governor system suggests a control systems approach (cs.SY). The paper also mentions the use of directional preference and adaptation to local environment geometry, which could fall under artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The use of a quadratic state-dependent distance metric could also suggest machine learning or optimization (cs.LG). Finally, the paper mentions collision avoidance, which is a common topic in computer vision (cs.CV).
